          "body": "At the chapter's theological center stands Jesus's Spirit-empowered prayer (10:21-22). The Father has hidden these things from the wise and intelligent and revealed them to infants — by His sovereign good pleasure (*eudokia*). This is one of the most explicit Father-Son disclosures in the Synoptics, often called the 'Johannine thunderbolt' for its resemblance to John's Gospel: all things handed over to the Son; mutual exclusive knowledge between Father and Son; revelation of the Father restricted to whomever the Son wills (10:22). The chapter's epistemology is therefore not democratic. The lawyer's clever question (10:29), Martha's many calculations (10:40), and the Galilean towns' presumption of privilege (10:13-15) all share the disability of *sophos kai sunetos* — wise and intelligent. The infants — the seventy returning with joy, Mary at His feet — receive what the credentialed cannot grasp."
